  "body": "*Description*:\r\n\r\nWhen the compressor or gzip filter is enabled, the `vary: accept-encoding` header is only set when the response is actually compressed. This can cause unexpected behaviour in caching proxies, depending on the order of the request.\r\n\r\n*Repro steps*:\r\n\r\nWith a regular caching proxy in front of envoy, and a cacheable & compressible response:\r\n\r\n1. `curl host/file.txt -v --compressed` - Compressed response is returned, expected.\r\n1. `curl host/file.txt -v` - Uncompressed response is returned, expected.\r\n\r\nClear proxy cache, and do the reverse:\r\n\r\n1. `curl host/file.txt -v` - Uncompressed response is returned, expected.\r\n1. `curl host/file.txt -v --compressed` - Uncompressed response is returned, **unexpected**!\r\n\r\n*How to fix:*\r\n\r\nEnvoy needs to always set `vary: accept-encoding` for any compressible responses. Otherwise, if an uncompressed response is cached, the proxy won't know to fetch a new incoming request with `Accept-Encoding: gzip` from upstream.",
